modified zmq_gen method to yield None when there is no waiting message. This prevents blocking in the next() method of a component. But it requires generators wrapping the component to handle None.Also modified component's receiver creation to be triggered on the first call to next, rather than iter.nThis change means that the zmq context and socket for the component's receiver should always be created innthe same process as the consumer of the generator. Chaining together component wrapped generators willnresult in the send process of the last component actually instantiating the receive socket of the prior component.nIn this way, the components are actually communicating directly via zmq.nnComponent's send method now calls the wait_ready(), which waits for the monitor's GO message, insidenthe generator loop. This guarantees that the generator's next method is called before the send loop blocksnon the monitor. As a result, components will call __init__ and next() without blocking, mimicking thenbehavior of plain generators.n

Provides an iterative version of risk metrics.I wrote this a little while ago as I noticed that a lot of time is spentncomputing risk statistics. This is done over the complete history overnand over again while this could be done just by using the previouslyncomputed value (iteratively).nnWe didn't go forward back then because for minute trade data thendifference was not significant enough. However, now with ziplinenstandalone I think most people will use daily (because that'snwhat's available) and it makes a huge differencen(speed-up of a couple of 100%).nnUnfortunately, we can't just replace the existing one with anniterative as for the final cumulative stats the batch is stillnbetter. So that's not as nice, but the performance increase isnbig enough for me to issue this PR (zipline is actually painfullynslow with daily data).nnThere is a unittest that compares that both produce exactlynthe same outputs.nnSpeed measurements (for 500 trading days, daily source):nnwith iterative:nreal 26.617 user 12.909 sys 6.112 pcpu 71.46nnprior:nreal 44.176 user 31.030 sys 11.381 pcpu 96.00n
Accounts for negative values when creating compounded returns.Sets the value sent to log to a value that doesn't crash out becausenof negative value.nSetting the value to 0 instead.n

Changes tests from using an ndict for trades to an Event object.When run over large amounts of data the use of ndict's gets and setsnbecome a large bottleneck, around 1/5th of the CPU time is spentnin ndict's __setattr__, __getattr__, etc.nnBy switching to an object for an event,nwe reduce the penalty significantly.nnRemoves asserts that check for event being an ndict, as well as thosenthat assume a certain behavior of the __contains__ method for events.n

Optimizes checking ready state of sources during sorting.The main bottle neck here was using `len`.nA boolean check is a sufficient test for more items in the queue.nnAlso, uses all instead of several functions.n
Adds a __repr__ method for Event.

Removes assert of message confirming to protocol.Two reasons for removal:n- On the path of removing most non-postconditional asserts.n  Since the asserts on every message is incurring an  non-insignificant penalty on large datasets.n- Since the assert was invoked as a function, the 'right side'n  of the assert statement, i.e. the error message was being invokedn  as a function, discovered since the __repr__ of the message wasn  high on the bottleneck list.n
Removes assert of sort protocol in inner loop.Since this was invoked as an function, the invocation of the methodnwas not dropped by -O.nAlso, moving towards only having postconditional asserts.n

Removes timeout handling from simulator's simulate_snapshot.The delta was ensuring that the backtester wouldn't exceed thendelta of a bar if it were being run against live data.nnHowever, this extra overhead of getting the current time on eachnside of the handle_data adds a penalty in pure backtest mode.nnAlso, it makes the backtest results potentially non-repeatable,nsince it is sensitive to current conditions on a box for processingntime.nnFavoring having the timeout handled by whatever is running thenzipline algorithm.n

Exposes the list of trading days contained in a trading environment.Previously, the list was generated, but only used to calculatenthe number of days in the environment.nnWith exposing this list, working towards a path where the simulationnuses the trading days to determine when to handle market closes.n

Adds an init to protocol.Event to enable setting of initial values.So that an Event can use an initial dict to set all values,ninstead of needing to set initial values one by one.nni.e. enables:nn```nfoo = Event({'bar': 1, 'baz': 2})n```nnin favor of:nn```nfoo = Event()nfoo.bar = 1nfoo.baz = 2n```n

Uses dictionary update instead of iterating through keys.update_universe is a bottleneck on large data sets.nnA large portion of that bottleneck is the call to getitem whilenlooping over the keys, so using update while passing along the internaln__dict__nnSeeing about a 40% improvement.n
Changes date_sort to use heapq module.Uses heapq.merge to sort input from mulitple sources instead ofnour own sort module.nnFrom profiling heapq.merge is more efficient than our own efforts.n
Removes sort module.Sort module is now unneeded with use of heapq.mergennAlso adapts test_perf_tracking so that it uses date_sorted_sources.n

Uses a Portfolio object instead of an ndict.Gains some performance by using a 'regular' object instead ofnan ndict.nnAlso, directly sets up the values that we return, instead of going innbetween with __core_dict and then removing values.nnIn it's entirety performanc.as_portfolio is the currentnhighest bottleneck, working on reducing time spent in that function.n

Recycles the portfolio container to be passed to handle_data.The creation of a new portfolio ndict on each call of handle_datanwas creating a very high performance overhead.nnInstead, we use the same the portfolio object for each event,nand replace the values contained within.n

Recycles objects for positions.Instead of creating a new ndict for each position on every event,nwe change the values in the object that held the previous position.nnThe creation of new objects on each event was incurring too muchnoverhead.nnChanges the position type returned by performance module.nnFor improved speed, changes from ndict to a simple Python object,nsince the cost of setting ndict values is too expensive for thennumber of times that positions are returned.nnAlso, changes the containing type of the positions to be dictionarynwith the __missing__ overloaded, instead of the ndict that had thatnbehavior, to reduce the penalty of using ndicts.n

Rolls over existing PerformancePeriod.Instead of doing the rollover by creating a new PerformancePeriod,nintroduces a `rollover` method that resets the values that neednto be fresh in a new period, and moves the ending values to startingnvalues, and leaves positions intact.nnThis isn't a major runtime improvement in of itself, but it doesnallow us to more easily keep track of position values from periodnto period, which other improvements will use.n

Uses vdot and numpy arrays for position totals.Gets almost 100x speed up over iterating over the values andnsumming up the values in Python.nnFarms out the work to numpy and atlas by using the vector dotnproduct of the amounts and last sale prices.nnAdds some wiring of keeping track of an index into the numpy arraysnfor each position, so that value can be overwritten as events updatenthose amounts and sale prices.n

Fixes dates used in test factory for batch transforms.The test factory was creating non-market days.ni.e. the date range spanned the weekend.nnUsing pandas' BDay frequency so that only business days are created.nnThis specific date range doesn't have holidays, so not accountingnfor holidays in the factory.nnAlso, widens the range of the trading calendar to cover the test datesngenerated by the factory which include 1990.nPreviously the trading calendar began with 2002, meaning that holidaynand weekend adjustments with the data exercised by the factory didnnot trigger when run with data in 1990.nnThis does increase the memory footprint of the tradingcalendar module.nHowever, only by a couple MB, so taking the hit there to enablencorrect behavior.n

Adds dividends to performance tracking.Algorithm returns and the risk calculations that depend on them now includencash dividends. This commit does _not_ provide an API for user algorithms tonaccess dividends.nnPerformanceTracker expects the dividend data to arrive as events, similar tonthe way that Trades arrive. Dividends are expected to have adjusted paymentnamounts that are inline with adjusted trades.nnPerformanceTracker maintains state of all the unpaid dividends in the positionnobjects held in PerformancePeriod. Dividend objects contain all the relevantndates (declared, ex, payment) as well as net and gross amounts. Dividends arenremoved from the list as they are paid. Cash flow is not incremented until thenpayment day. This creates the possibility of a dividend being owed but notnpaid or realized before the end of a test. For example, a dividend with annex_date of today may have a pay date 2 weeks in the future. Right now thenalgorithm does not receive any credit for unpaid dividends.nnTests cover buying/selling around the ex_date and payment_date, and checkingnthat the performance calculated is as expected.n

Fixed bugs in the sequence of dividend payment calculations. Previously, we were using midnight of the current trading day in market close. That meant that we were rewinding the clock, and then checking the ex_date and pay_date. As a result, we were delaying payments by one day.With this patch, on the close of markets we fast forward to midnight of thennext trading day and calculate the dividend payments. This patch assumes thatnthe dividend dates are all at midnight UTC.n

Changes the API for recording variables.Uses a method called 'record' that provides a key value,ninstead of providing keys to extract from context.nnThe variables are stored internally to the algorithm in a dictionary,nand not just stared as a property of the algorithm.nnMain intent behind this change is to make the API more user friendly,nsince the previous recorded_variables relies on the value to be setnin the algorithms context/self, the hope is that only having to usenthe `record` method means less moving pieces and a more understandablenAPI.nni.e., instead of:nn```ndef initialize(self):nrecorded_variables('foo', bar')nndef handle_data(self, data):nself.foo = 1nself.bar = 2n```nnThe API is now:nn```ndef initialize(self):npassnndef handle_data(self, data):nself.record(foo=1, bar=2)n```n

But with minutesnyou update with the first minute bar of the day which is not correct.nnThis is fixed by calculating the market_close explicity and seeing whether thenevent.dt is on or past it.nnI also added a unittest to test the correct behavior of this.n

MAINT: Remove check in slippage model which is always true.Since `cur_amount` before it's changed by the direction, is alwaysna positive value, multiplying it back by the direction should alsonalways be positive.n

MAINT: Separate volume and direction while calculating volume share.In the volume share slippgae, the current amount had the direction,ni.e. buy/sell was baked into the value of `cur_amount` which thennneeded to have the direction multiplied out when parts of the slippagenmodel needed to take in just the magnitude/amount into account.nnSo calculate the current volume, use that in calculations and thennapply at the order direction at order time.nnAlso, when applying the direction to the magnitude of the sell,nuse copysign to make the code more explicit about taking the directionnof the order, instead of it possibly having some scalar impact.nnAs well as remove direction from volume_share calculation since thatncalculation and subsequent calculations only care about the magnitude,nso make the disregard for direction more explicit by removing it.n
MAINT: Factor out order processing from slippage models.Step towards having a shared simulate method in the base SlippageModel,nwhich would call a process_order method in each model.n

BUG: Use context in lieu of use_environment decoratorThe use_environment decorator is too side-effectful (e.g.,nconnecting to Yahoo! Finance or another data source) to be used as andecorator to a function that gets evaluated during module load. Thisncauses problems, e.g., if Zipline is being used in a geventnenvironment, when the trading environment created by the decoratornargument tries to use greenlets when gevent hasn't been fullyninitialized.nnSince the decorator is nothing more than a context-manager wrapper,nthis commit removes the decorator and replaces its use with contexts,ni.e., with statements.n

Add a VirtualBox-based Vagrant config file.This VagrantFile will, on vagrant up...nn- Create a simple, minimal Precise Pangolin (12.04) Ubuntu 64 bit VMn- Customize the VM with 2 virtual CPU's and 2048MB of RAMn- Configure SSH for passwordless access (from the command-line)n- Add the required packages from the Ubuntu repo to support ziplinen- Add (and compile) ta-libn- Add the required Pip packagesnnWhen Vagrant is done, you can start hacking on zipline with:nnvagrant sshncd /vagrantnpython {some python script that uses zipline}nIn the spirit of making this a disposable dev environment installneverything in site-packages.nnnosetests and examples/dual_moving_average.py both succeednafter the configuration finishes.n

MAINT: Use DatetimeIndex instead of OrderedDict for trading days.Looking forwards to Python 3 capability, maintaing code that usesniterkeys would require some overhead of checking what Python versionnis available etc., instead use a DatetimeIndex so there is no neednto use key iterators, reverse, etc. on an OrderedDict, as thenDatetimeIndex allows 0 and -1 index, as well as the needed fast `in`nfunctionality.n

MAINT: Use explicit syntax for relative imports.Python 3 requires using dot syntax for relative imports,notherwise the import is treated as an absolute import, i.e.nan import of a module from outside of the project.nnBy using dot syntax now, imports should be compatible with bothnPython 2.7 and Python 3.n

BUG: Trading calendar dates should always be midnight UTCFor consistency, datetimes returned by the trading calendar shouldnalways show HHMMSS of midnight UTC. Not only is this useful fornconsistency, but it also allows us to check if a particular date() isnin an array of these datetimes, because they will hash to the samenthing. For example:nnearly_closes = get_early_closes()n... later ...nif current_bar_datetime.date() in early_closes:n... today closes early ...nnIf if the datetimes returned by the trading calendar functions don'tnhave 00:00:00 for HHMMSS, then the in check above will fail becausenthe date and the datetimes in early_closes won't hash to the samenthing.n

TST: Defend against non-trading days as period start in commission test.A bug in the create_random_simulation_parameters allows the periodnstart to be a non-trading day.nnThat bug was causing the commission tests to randomly fail, e.g.nwhen the period start was on Good Friday, because the commission wasncreated on hour three of Good Friday, instead of the next Monday.nWhen it hit that case, the test commission is never processed.nnDefend against that bug by using the first open of the simulationnparameters which is more guaranteed to be during market hours,nwhen creating the test commission.nnThis is in place of fixing the bug in the random parameters functionnor making the parameters non-random, which are other potential fixes.n

MAINT: print function clean up in preparation for Python 3- Use `print()` function for all print callsn- Fix strip and format calls that were on the outside of then  print function for some reason.n  (Which were breaking in Python 3 because of print returning None.)n- Remove commented out print calls.n

MAINT: Updated librariesiso8601, pytz, numpy, python-dateutil, six, Cython, requests,nnnose-parameterized, nose-ignore-docstring, scipy, matplotlib,npatsynnNote that patsy must install before statsmodels.n

MAINT: Use six for Python 3 compatible names and behavior.Use the six module to import functions and types that arenconsistent between Python 2 and 3, so that one code base cannsupport both versions.nn- Use integer types instead of int and long.n- Use string_types instead of basestring.n- Account for iteritems, itervalues, iterkeys.n- Use six.moves for filter and zip, reducen- Use compatible bytes for md5 hasher.n- xrange and rangen

MAINT: Use explicit relative pathing for Python 3 compatibility.Python 3 requires submodules to have more explicit pathing, so usenthe dot syntax to declare submodules which are in the same directorynas another module.n
MAINT: Make answer key reading compatible with Python 3.Ensure reading of bytes and checking against byte type, whennparsing the Excel spreadsheet which contains the answers.n

MAINT: Explicitly convert map to list when converting answer key values.For compatibility with iterator version of map in Python 3.nnAlso always use iterator version of map,nso that code path is exercised in Python 2.n

MAINT: Remove type checking which trip up Python 3 compatibility.Instead of porting these cases of type checking, remove them instead.nSlightly more Python-ic to be more generous in what is allowed, andnthe conversion to make these compatible with Python 3 are more troublenthan they are worth.n

MAINT: Support both Python 2 and 3 next interfaces.Python 3 uses the `__next__` method instead of `next`,nand uses the syntax of `next(foo)` accordingly.nnAdd `__next__` and `next` side-by-side so both Python 2 and 3 havena method that can be used during iteration.n

MAINT: Make walk usage in example tests compatible with Python 3The rename of walk is not provided by six, so check the import errornvia an exception.nnAlso, callback behavior slightly changes between the two versions,nso instead iterate over the walked files and call what was formerlyna callback, directly as a function.n

MAINT: Make exception handling tests compatible between Python 2 and 3Python 3 removes the `.message` attribute, so use `str` instead.nnAlso, the divide by zero message has changed slightly between versions,nso just check for the exception type, instead of also checking the message.n

MAINT: Adjust for comparison changes in Python 3.Use date sorted sources instead, instead of sorting with secondnargument of Event, etc. since the `heapq.merge` behavior is usingnthe second part of the tuple, thus requiring a richer set of comparisonnmethods, which would only be used in the test context.nnUse `date_sorted_sources` instead, so that sorting is done on algo timenand source id.n

MAINT: Use Python 3 compatible metaclass.Use six's with_metaclass to have objects that use metaclasses, innboth Python 2 and 3.nnOtherwise, in Python 3 the objects were being treated as if theyndid not have a metaclass, when the Python 2 syntax is used, leadingnto errors because of missing attributes, etc.n
MAINT: Read text in Python 3 instead of bytes when fetching public data.Account for byte/string compatibility when consuming response fromnrequests module.n

MAINT: Use pandas for data cache file I/OThe compatibility between the two versions was made easier bynletting pandas handle the heavy lifting, so pass filenames to thenpandas serialization methods, instead of dealing doing the filenhandling and reading/writing within the data module.n
BLD: Use Python 3 on Travis.To help prevent regressions when a changes are developed usingnPython 2.7, also test Python 3 during continuous integration.n
Merge Python 3 compatibility branch.This branch should make it so that the code base can be runnusing both Python 2.7 and Python 3.3n

BUG: Fix check for cached public data for Python 2.7Python 2 and 3 throw different exception types when a file doesnnot exist.nnCatch both exception types to trigger the download, so that thenloader works under both Python versions.n
BUG: Make write of binary file compatible with Python 3.Open the destination file with the byte flag to avoid error innPython 3 with mismatch of str and byte.n

PERF: Remove alias_dt transform in favor of property on SIDData.Adding a copy of the Event's dt field as datetime via then`alias_dt` generator, so that the API was forgiving and allowednboth datetime and dt on a SIDData object, was creating noticeablenoverhead, even on an noop algorithms.nnInstead of incurring the cost of copying the datetime value andnassigning it to the Event object on every event that is passednthrough the system, add a property to SIDData which acts as annalias `datetime` to `dt`.nnEventually support for `data['foo'].datetime` may be removed,nand could be considered deprecated.n

MAINT: More precise extraction of returns from returns container.Use slice to date, `[:dt]` instead of `pd.Series.valid` to extractnfrom returns containers.nnUsing `valid` lead to some confusion when debugging tests, becausenit papers over missing data.nnThe use of `.valid` was based on the assumption that all valuesnfrom the zeroth date to the current algo date are populated,nwith no trailing values.n`[:dt]` extracts the same data, but in a hopefully more precisenand explicit fashion.n

TST: Disable talib default params test.The data zipline_transform.window is always evaluating to empty,nthus the actual checks are not being used because of then`if not data` done before running the `asserts`.nnThis behavior should be fixed, and we should either remove then`not data` check, or bubble up that the check is being hit toonmany times; but in the meantime, disabling this test which takesna non-trivial amount of time to run.nnWhen run as an algorithm, outside of unit tests the talib wrapperndoes work, so the cause of the window always being empty may be tondue to the machinery of the unit test.n

MAINT: Use current_data instead of last_sale_priceIt seems more clear to get price values fromn`self.trading_client.current_data[sid].price` thannfrom `self.portfolio.positions[sid].last_sale_price`.nnThe two values are the same, so this is just a readability change,nbut it is also the same behavior as in `self.order_value()` and it'sngood to have them all be the same.n

BUG: Fix misalignment of downside series calc when using exact dates.An oddity that was exposed while working on making the return seriesnpassed to the risk module more exact, the series comparison betweennthe returns and mean returns was unbalanced, because the mean returnsnwere not masked down to the downside data points; however, in most,nif not all cases this was papered over by the call to `.valid()`n

BUG: Prevent out of sync market closes in performance tracker.In situations where the performance tracker has been reset or patchednto handle state juggling with warming up live data, the `market_close`nmember of the performance tracker could end up out of sync with thencurrent algo time as determined by thennThe symptom was dividends never triggering, because the end of daynchecks would not match the current time.nnFix by having the tradesimulation loop be responsible, in minute/minutenmode, for advancing the market close and passing that value to thenperformance tracker, instead of having the market close advanced bynthe performance tracker as well.n

ENH: Remove dependency on benchmark for trading day calendar.Instead of the benchmarks' index, use the trading calendar tonpopulate the environment's trading days.nnRemove `extra_date` field, since unlike the benchmarks list,nthe trading calendar can generate future dates, so dates forncurrent day trading do not need to be appended.nnMotivations:n- The source for the open and close/early close calendar and then  trading day calendar is now the same, which should help preventn  potential issues due to misalignment.n- Allows configurations where the benchmark is provided as an  generator based data source to need to supply a second benchmarkn  list just to populate dates.n

TST: Use benchmark returns from spreadsheet.The risk unit tests were using the public Yahoo! data insteadnof the returns from the answer key spreadsheet, change the RiskPeriod'sncreated in tests to use the values in the benchmark returnsncolumn of the answer key.nnAlso, change the spreadsheet's benchmark volatility calculationnto use sample.nThe use of population was exposed when the input values werencorrected.n

BUG: Fix numerous cumulative and period risk calculations.The calculations that are expected to change are:n- cumulative.betan- cumulative.alphan- cumulative.informationn- cumulative.sharpen- period.sortinonn* Explanation of how risk calculations are changingnn** Risk Fixes for Both Period and Cumulativenn*** Downside Risknn   Use sample instead of population for standard deviation.nn   Add a rounding factor, so that if the two values are close for a givenn   dt, that they do not count as a downside value, which would throw offn   the denominator of the standard deviation of the downside diffs.nn*** Standard Deviation TypennAcross the board the standard deviation has been standardized to usingna 'sample' calculation, whereas before cumulative risk was monstly usingn'population'. Using `ddof=1` with `np.std` calculates as if the valuesnare a sample.nn** Cumulative Risk Fixesnn*** Betann   Use the daily algorithm returns and benchmarks instead of annualizedn   mean returns.nn*** Volatilitynn   Use sample instead of population with standard deviation.nn   The volatility is an input to other calculations so this change affectsn   Sharpe and Information ratio calculations.nn*** Information Rationn   The benchmark returns input is changed from annualized benchmark returnsn   to the annualized mean returns.nn*** Alphann   The benchmark returns input is changed from annualized benchmark returnsn   to the annualized mean returns.nn** Period Risk Fixesnn*** SortinonnUse the downside risk of the daily return vs. the mean algorithm returnsnfor the minimum acceptable return instead of the treasury return.nnThe above required adding the calculation of the mean algorithm returnsnfor period risk.nnAlso, use algorithm_period_returns and tresaury_period_return as thencumulative Sortino does, instead of using algorithm returns for bothninputs into the Sortino calculation.nn* Other Supporting Changesnn** answer_keynn   Add new mappings for downside risk and Sortino as well asn   re-address the index mappings because of changes to the answer keyn   spread sheet.nn** test_risk_cumulativenn   Change the decimal precision to expect higher precision.n   The calculations are now more aligned with the answer key, so we cann   expect higher precision. In particular now that the standard deviationn   type matches everywhere in both the Python implementation and the answern   sheet, the precision of the first value no longer has to be glossed over.nn** test_events_through_risknn  Change the results which are used as a canary for risk changes,n  since we do expect Sharpe to change with this change..n

BUG: Fix change of type of period.sharpeThe factoring out of the Sharpe calculation changed behaviornso that both period and cumulative return nans when there isnno volatility; however before that change period returned 0.0.nnThis breaks existing consumers which expected a non-nan valuenfor period results.nnSmooth out that change by checking the value after the sharpenhas been calculated and reset nan's to 0.0n

PERF: Remove the drop of 'null return' from cumulative returns.The check of existence of the null return key, and the drop of saidnreturn on every single bar was adding unneeded CPU time when annalgorithm was run with minute emissions.nnInstead, add the 0.0 return with an index of the trading day beforenthe start date.nnThe removal of the `null return` was mainly in place so that thenperiod calculation was not crashing on a non-date index value;nwith the index as a date, the period return can also approximatenvolatility (even though the that volatility has high noise-to-signalnstrength because it uses only two values as an input.)n
PERF: Reduce number of times the downside mask is created.Assign the downside mask, `rets < mar` to a value instead ofncalculating the downsides twice.n

ENH: Update ordering API to support new ExecutionStyle class in favor of existing `limit_price` and `stop_price` parameters.  The goal of this change is to refactor the existing ordering API to provide a cleaner interface for defining more complex order types.Adds a new module, zipline.finance.execution, which defines the ExecutionStylenabstract base class, along with concrete MarketOrder, LimitOrder, StopOrder,nand StopLimitOrder subclasses.nnAdds a new `style` keyword argument to the function signature of the `order`nAPI method, which accepts an instance of ExecutionStyle.nnThe existing limit_price and stop_price parameters are still supported at thisntime, but are converted into the new ExecutionStyle objects before being passednto Blotter.order.n

ENH: Add style parameters to order API helper methods.Add `style` parameter to order_value, order_percent, order_target,norder_target_percent, and order_target_value methods.  The style parameter isnforwarded to the underlying call to `order`.n

ENH: Allow for stock dividends, and in particular, Google'srecent 2 for 1 stock split, where 1 class C share was distributednfor each share of class A held.nnNow a dividend can specify a sid and ratio of stock that will be paidnto owners of the original security.  If the ratio is 2.0, then for everynexisting share, two shares will be paid.n
DOC: Replaced i.e. with e.g. where appropriate in module

ENH: Treat stop and limit prices differently when rounding.Stop and limit prices both trigger when a price crosses some threshold, butnthey trigger in opposite directions.  For example, on a buy, a limit price isntriggered when a price falls below a specified value, whereas a stop pricentriggers when the price exceeds a specified value.nnOur current stop/limit price rounding logic is asymmetric, preferring to roundnto improve the specified price.  This change makes it so that we interpretnimprovement in opposite directions for stop vs limit prices.n

ENH: Add trading controls to zipline API.Adds four new methods to the Zipline API that can be used as circuit-breakersnto interrupt the execution of an algorithm.  The API methods are:nn`set_max_position_size`n`set_max_order_size`n`set_max_order_count`n`set_long_only`nnInternally, these methods are implemented by each registering a TradingControlncallback object with the TradingAlgorithm.  DuringnTradingAlgorithm.__validate_order_params (and thus before any side-effects ofnthe order call occur), each callback's `validate` method is called withninformation about the order to be placed and the algorithm's current state,nraising an exception if the callback detects that an error condition has been breached.n

PERF/BUG: Make the portfolio property call `updated_portfolio`.Make the portfolio property on TradingAlgorithm call `updated_portfolio`ninternally.  This prevents needless recomputation of the portfolio betweenncalls to `handle_data`, and also prevents issues where the portfolio objectncould be unexpectedly modified in place in the body of a `handle_data` call.nnNoteworthy finding in the course of investigating this bug:nnIf you modify a Python dictionary while iterating over it, the language willnonly throw an exception if the size of the dictionary changes between loopniterations; this means that you can do:n```nx = {1:1, 2:2, 3:3}nfor k in x:nold_val = x[k]ndel x[k]nx[f(k)] = old_valnprint kn```nand you'll only get an error if f(k) is already a key in the dictionary.nThis can lead to bizarre/nondeterministic behavior in the key iterator.n

ENH: Enhancements to `TradingEnvironment`.Adds a suite of new functions for querying data from the trading calendar.nnThese include:n  `previous_trading_day`n  `minutes_for_days_in_range` (minutely version of `days_in_range`)n  `previous_open_and_close` (inverse of `next_open_and_close`)n  `next_market_minute`n  `previous_market_minute`n  `open_close_window` (get a range of opens/closes with slicing semantics)n  `market_minute_window` (get a range of minutes with slicing semantics)nnAlso refactors `test_finance` to move `TradingEnvironment` tests into their ownnTestCase.n

ENH: Prep work for supporting '1m' history.Overhauls `HistoryContainer` in prep for support of more than one frequency.nnMajor changes:nn   - Methods/variables referring to day have been renamed/generalized.n - `current_day_panel` became `buffer_panel`, which is now a `RollingPanel`n - `prior_day_panel` became a dictionary mapping `Frequency` objects ton   digest panels, which are instances of `RollingPanel`.nn   - Hard-coded daily rollover replaced with a notion of a current window forn each unique frequency managed by the panel.nn - When the end of the current window is reached for a given frequency, wen   compute an aggregate bar (code refers to this as a digest), which isn   appended to a panel associated with that frequency.nn - Window rollover dates are managed by a pair of dictionaries,n   `cur_window_starts` and `cur_window_closes`.  The `Frequency` class isn   responsible for computing window bounds based on the open/close of then   previous window.nn   - Semantic change to the `open_price` field: `open_price` now alwaysn contains the price of the first trade occurring in the given window.n Previously it contained the price of the first minute in the window,n returning NaN it the security happened not to trade in the first minute.n
BUG: Don't return mostly nans from `get_history` when `ffill=False`.Fixes an issue where, if `ffill=False`, `get_history` would return nans fornevery entry in the history frame except the last one.n

BUG: History no longer fails on length-1 '1m' price-only HistorySpecsThe bug occurred because there is a special case in the initial window setupncode for handling the case where only a length-1 history is used for a givennfrequency.  Previously, the code was incorrectly calculating the period endnusing a hard-coded expression for the end of the day (the correct behavior forna length-1 '1d' history), and then using the frequency object to calculate thenperiod start for the window.  In the case of length 1 '1m' data, this resultednin an initial window whose start and end was the last minute of the day rathernthan the first minute of the day.  For non-price fields, this error doesn'tnmatter, because the window is only used for rolling digests (which doesn'tnhappen when there's only a length-1 history), and for the forward-filling logicn(which only happens on price fields).  For a length-1 '1m' price, however, thenincorrect window causes us to attempt to forward-fill an empty panel, resultingnin an IndexError when we do an iloc[0] on a length-0 axis.n

PERF: Replace .ix usages with with .loc in TradingEnvironment.Replace usage of .ix in TradingEnvironment with .loc when we know that we'renusing an index key.nnDataFrame.ix can be used with either integer or key-based indices, and as suchnit incurs an overhead for figuring out which you meant.n

MAINT: One way to set sim_params and data_frequency.There were sevaral places you could supply sim_paramsnin TradingAlgorithm (__init__, run). This got confusingnas its not clear who updated what and which one was thencorrect one to use at each time.nnThen there were to ways to define data_frequency, one inn__init__() and one in the sim_params which also added codencomplexity.nnThis refactor makes it explicit that sim_params are to benpassed to __init__() only. Moreover, data_frequency isnonly stored in sim_params. For backwards compatibility,nit can still be supplied separately but will link tonthe one in sim_params.nnFor example, you could create new sim params via:nnsim_params = create_simulation_parameters(data_frequency='minute')nalgo = MyAlgo(sim_params)nalgo.run(data)nnIn addition, perf_tracker only gets initialized in one place:n_create_generator() which should also make the various waysnof running an algorithm more deterministic.nnThis also fixes a bug with SimulationParameters wherenyou could not change the period_start. Unfortunately, thencurrent implementation still requieres an implicit call tonupdate the internal variables.n

BUG: Algo no longer crashes after creating new history column.Fixes an issue that caused a crash if a user assigned a new column into anreturned history DataFrame. We should re-evaluate this implementation when we're on a more modernnpandas version.n

DEV: Overhaul core history logic.Overhaul the core HistoryContainer logic to be more robust to changingnuniverses.nnMajor Changesn-------------n* Remove `return_frame` cache.  The original purpose of usingn  return_frames was to avoid having to create new DataFrames on eachn  iteration of handle_data, but we ended up having to copy the returnn  frames anyway because user code could mutate the frames in place.n  Removing the return_frames reduces unnecessary copying, and reducesn  the logic of `get_history` to just forward-filling and concatenatingn  two DataFrames.nn* Use a `MultiIndex`ed DataFrame to representn  `last_known_prior_values`.  This makes lookups faster and greatlyn  simplifies the logic of adding and dropping sids.nn* HistoryContainer no longer attempts to determine its universe based onn  the contents of its internal buffers.  The TradingAlgorithmn  controlling the container is now responsible for explicitly callingn  `add_sids` or `drop_sids` when securities enter or leave then  algorithm's universe.  These methods, along with the internaln  `_realign` method, provide a clean interface for changing the universen  of securities managed by the container.nn* Refactor index mutation logic in `RollingPanel` into an  `MutableIndexRollingPanel` subclass.  Maintenance of the old behaviorn  is regrettably necessary to support `BatchTransform`.nn* Refactor shared logic from `roll` and `get_history` into a singlen  `aggregate_ohlcv_panel` method that's responsible for collapsing ann  OHLCV buffer into a frame.n

PERF: History Perf EnhancementsLimited use of `pandas` data structures in both `HistoryContainer` andn`RollingPanel`. Where possible, methods were amended to return rawn`ndarrays` with the indexing logic done separately. This allows us toncut down the number of times pandas objects are created both as returnsnand intermediate values. The separation of indexing from data accessnallowed us to minimize the times weu00e2u0080u0099d make use of pandas indexes.nnThis required that that certain methods like `NDFrame.ffill` be replacednwith versions that work with `ndarrays`. Some of this was done vianstraight numpy methods and others by access pandas internalnmachinery. Outside of allowing us to use faster ndarrays, many of thesenfunction provided speedups over their pandas counterparts as we didnu00e2u0080u0099tnrequire the extra features like handling multiple dtypes. i.e. np.isnannis faster than pd.isnull, but only works with certain dtypes.n

ENH Allow order_percent to work with various market valuesCurrently, `order_percent()` and `order_target_percent()` both operate as a percentage of `self.portfolio.portfolio_value`. This PR lets them operate as percentages of other important MVs.nn(also adds `context.get_market_value()`, which enables this functionality)nnFor example:n```pythonnorder_percent('AAPL', 0.5)nnorder_percent('AAPL', 0.5, percent_of='cash')nnorder_target_percent('MSFT', 0.1, percent_of='shorts')nntech_stocks = ('AAPL', 'MSFT', 'GOOGL')ntech_filter = lambda p: p.sid in tech_stocksnfor stock in tech_stocks:norder_target_percent(stock, 1/3, percent_of_fn=tech_filter)n```n

TST: Use pandas relativedelta for calendar end to account for leap year.Some unit tests for test_tradingcalendar failed on 2015-03-01, because thenaddition of 365 days put the end date at 2016-02-29; when the replacesnthe year on that date it fails because there is no 2017-02-29.nnInstead use relativedelta with a year argument which accounts for leapnyears.nnFixes the following test failure:nn```n======================================================================nERROR: test_day_after_thanksgiving (tests.test_tradingcalendar.TestTradingCalendar)n----------------------------------------------------------------------nTraceback (most recent call last):n  File ./tests/test_tradingcalendar.py, line 211, in test_day_after_thanksgivingntradingcalendar.end.replace(year=tradingcalendar.end.year + 1)n  File tslib.pyx, line 297, in pandas.tslib.Timestamp.replace (pandas/tslib.c:7325)nValueError: day is out of range for monthnn----------------------------------------------------------------------nRan 1 test in 0.001sn```n

BUG: Stop account_needs_update from blocking performance updatesReferencing context.account in handle_data() can block updates to account,nportfolio and performance metrics, which can cause unintended changes innfinancial performance. PERF: Change asset finder to be backed by sqlite3.Attack the startup bottleneck of creating the asset finders caches for anlarge universe, which was between 1-2 seconds on development andnproduction machines.nnInstead, allow the AssetFinder to be passed a sqlite3 file that hasnalready been populated and then hydrate asset objects only when annequity is referenced for the first time.nnTo create aforementioned sqlite3, create an AssetFinder with an db_pathnand `create_table` set to True. If `create_table` is set to False, thenprepopulated data in the sqlite file found at db_path will be used.nnDefault behavior is to use an in memory database.nnBehavior that changes:nn- Fuzzy lookup now only works on one character, that character needs to benspecified at write/metadata consumption time, since the fuzzy lookup keynis created by dropping the character from each symbol.nn- Overwriting partially written metadata is no longern  supported. i.e. some unit tests allowed for inserting just the identifier,n  and then later updating the symbol, end_date, etc.nn  Instead of building an upsert behavior at this time, this patchn  changes the unit tests so that the data for each asset is onlyn  inserted once.nnOther notes:nn- populate_cache is now removed, since there is no longer a two stepn  process of inserting metadata and then realizing that metadata inton  assets. _spawn_asset is rolled into insert_metadata, so that a call ton  insert_metadata both converts the metadata and makes it available inn  the data store.n

ENH: Compute engine architecture for FFC API.This patch lays the groundwork for a compute engine designed tonfacilitate construction of factor-based universe screening and portfolionallocation.  It contains:nnA new module, `zipline.modelling`, containing entities that can be usednto express computations as dependency graphs.  Each node in such a graphnis an instance of the base `Term` class, defined inn`zipline.modelling.term`.  Dependency graphs are executed by instancesnof `FFCEngine`, defined in `zipline.modelling.engine`.nnA new module, `zipline.data.ffc`, containing loaders and datasetndefinitions for inputs to the modelling API.nnNew `TradingAlgorithm` api methods: `add_factor`, and `add_filter`.nThese methods can only be called from `initialize`, and are used toninform the algorithm that each day it should compute the given terms.nComputed factor results are made available through a new attribute ofnthe `data` object in `before_trading_start` and `handle_data`.  Computednfilter results control which assets are available in the factor matrixnon each day.n

ENH: Return asset-indexed DataFrame for data.factors.This makes ordering with the returned assets much easier, and there's nonperformance degradation for non-broadcasting operations on the Index.nnTimingsn-------nnfrom random import samplenfinder = AssetFinder(create_table=False, assets.db')nassets = load_8000_assets(finder)nAAPL = finder.retrieve_asset(24)nRANDOM_ASSETS = sample(assets, 500)ndf = DataFrame(nindex=assets,ndata=np.random.randn(len(assets), 4),ncolumns=['a', 'b', 'c', 'd'],n)ndf_int = DataFrame(nindex=map(int, assets),ndata=np.random.randn(len(assets), 4),ncolumns=['a', 'b', 'c', 'd'],n)nn%timeit df.loc[24]n%timeit df_int.loc[24]nn10000 loops, best of 3: 45.3 u00c2u00b5s per loopn10000 loops, best of 3: 44.7 u00c2u00b5s per loopnn%timeit df.loc[AAPL]n%timeit df_int.loc[AAPL]nn10000 loops, best of 3: 45.1 u00c2u00b5s per loopn10000 loops, best of 3: 44.8 u00c2u00b5s per loopnn%timeit df.loc[RANDOM_ASSETS]n%timeit df_int.loc[RANDOM_ASSETS]nn1000 loops, best of 3: 1.53 ms per loopn100 loops, best of 3: 2.18 ms per loopnn%timeit df.sum()n%timeit df_int.sum()nn10000 loops, best of 3: 56 u00c2u00b5s per loopn10000 loops, best of 3: 55.7 u00c2u00b5s per loopnn%timeit df.index == 3n%timeit df_int.index == 3nn1000 loops, best of 3: 253 u00c2u00b5s per loopn100000 loops, best of 3: 6.76 u00c2u00b5s per loopnn%timeit df.iloc[:50]n%timeit df_int.iloc[:50]nn10000 loops, best of 3: 44.3 u00c2u00b5s per loopn10000 loops, best of 3: 44 u00c2u00b5s per loopn

MAINT: Only calc position values once per packet.Instead of calculating the position values for each stat result, e.g.ngross_exposure, net_liquidity etc.; get the positions upfront and thenncalculate the period and position stats in order, passing each valuenexplicitly to the ones that follow it in the dependency chain.nne.g. the gross_value depends on the long_value and the short_value,nwhich called the position_values property for calculating both thenlong_value and the short_value.nnRemoving the repeated calls to position_values (andnposition_exposures) removes the need for the caching the last salenprices and position amounts in separate vectors, since it is inexpensivenenough to read those values off of the positions dictionary held in thenposition tracker.nnThis patch gives a small gain to ~500 sized portfolios, but the mainnintent is to clear the path to not storing last_sale_prices on thenposition objects at all. Removing all of the caching layer in this classnmakes that change easier to apply. Removing the extra calls tonposition_values also made this class easier to step through/reason aboutnwhen splicing in the new last sale price access, as well.n

ENH: Coerce user input with API method decoratorPreviously we have capitalized input strings at different levels innour code: in the user-facing API methods and in the asset finder.nThis commit moves input string capitalization exclusively to the APInmethod to which the string was supplied. Specifically, the string isncapitalized by a preprocess API method decorator. The preprocessndecorator passes the input string to the newly definednensure_upper_case() method, which returns a TypeError if the argumentnsupplied is not a string.nnensure_upper_case() is defined in a new file, zipline/utils/input_validation.py.nThe existing expect_types() method is also moved there.nnVarious tests in tests/test_assets.py are modified to account for thenfact that the asset finder method lookup_symol() no longer capitalizesnits supplied argument.n

PERF: Speed up reading of adjustments.For a pipeline doing simple computations on USEquityPricing data, wenwere spending ~60% of `run_pipeline` loading adjustments.  Almost all ofnthat time was spent in calls to `DatetimeIndex.get_loc` to find thenindices of adjustment `eff_date`s.nnThis optimizes the eff_date lookups by pre-populating a cache ofnseconds-since-epoch timestamps that we expect to see, and falling backnto `np.searchsorted` on cache misses.nnIn testing, this reduces the time to compute a 1-year pipeline with 30nand 90 day moving averages from 3.1 seconds to 0.9 seconds.n

ENH: Rewrite treasury loader using pandas.Replaces our custom XML parsing with a single call to `pd.read_csv`nagainst the federal reserve's API.  This produces nearly identicalnresults as compared to the old loader, but it's dramatically simpler andnroughly 10x faster on my machine.nnThe average difference in magnitude between new and old is approximatelyn10e-7, and only one entry is different to a degree greater than thennumber of significant figures provided by treasury.gov.nnAdditionally, the new loader correctly ignores Columbus Day of 2010, fornwhich the old loader erroneously produced an all-NaN row.nnThis also changes the interface that treasury modules modules arenrequired to implement. Modules must now supply a `get_treasury_data`nfunction that returns a `DataFrame` with a daily `DatetimeIndex` and ancolumn for each supported treasury duration.nnDetailed comparison between results from new and old loader::nnfrom zipline.data.treasuries import get_treasury_datannew = get_treasury_data() # New implementationnold = pd.read_csv(  # Previously cached datan'/home/ssanderson/.zipline/data/treasury_curves.csv'nparse_dates=[0],nindex_col=0,n)n# These columns were unused.ndel old['tid']; del old['date']nold = old.tz_localize('UTC')nold.dropna(how='all')n# old data erroneously contained an all-NaN entry for Columbus Dayn# in 2010.  Remove before comparing.nold = old.dropna(how='all')nnIn [25]: len(new) == len(old)nOut[25]: TruennIn [26]: abs(old - new).max()nOut[26]:n10year2.000000e-04n1month6.938894e-18n1year 1.000000e-04n20year1.000000e-04n2year 2.000000e-04n30year1.000000e-04n3month1.000000e-03n3year 1.000000e-04n5year 1.387779e-17n6month1.000000e-04n7year 1.000000e-04ndtype: float64nnIn [27]: abs(old - new).mean()nOut[27]:n10year3.097414e-08n1month4.396534e-19n1year 1.548707e-08n20year3.624502e-08n2year 4.646120e-08n30year1.830496e-08n3month1.549427e-07n3year 1.548707e-08n5year 1.702619e-18n6month1.548707e-08n7year 1.548707e-08ndtype: float64nnSince www.treasury.gov only reports values up to three significantndigits, we should only care about differences of greater than 1e-3.nnThere is exactly one such difference: the entry for the three month bondnon 1999-10-01::nnIn [60]: new[(abs(new - old) >= 1e-3).any(axis=1)].TnOut[60]:nTime Period  1999-10-01 00:00:00+00:00n1month NaNn3month  0.0498n6month  0.0501n1year   0.0530n2year   0.0573n3year   0.0583n5year   0.0590n7year   0.0622n10year  0.0600n20year  0.0657n30year  0.0615nnIn [61]: old[(abs(new - old) >= 1e-3).any(axis=1)].TnOut[61]:n1999-10-01 00:00:00+00:00n10year 0.0600n1monthNaNn1year  0.0530n20year 0.0657n2year  0.0573n30year 0.0615n3month 0.0488n3year  0.0583n5year  0.0590n6month 0.0501n7year  0.0622nnThe US Treasury website (our old source) provides a value of 0.488 here,nwhereas the Federal Reserve site (our new source) provides a value ofn0.498.n

MAINT: Futures cash adjustment on change and calc.In preparation for the incoming changes which no longer push every barnthrough the tradesimulation, remove the adjustment of the period's cash onnevery pricing change of a held futures asset.nnInstead hold the last sale price for each held future either:nn- At the end of each peformance period update the last sale prices ofn  all held futures, so that the pnl for the next period uses valuesn  derived from the cash difference between the end of the two periods.nn- When a transaction is processed for the Future, so that the correctn  amount is applied to each cash adjustment. (i.e. the cash adjustmentn  is reset on every change of amount of the Future being held, so thatn  multiple size and prices do not need to be tracked for the same asset.)nnAlso, remove now unused dict of payout calculation modifier, since newncalculation reads the value directly off of the asset.nnRemove update_last_sale test, since the method no longer returns a cashnvalue.n

BUG: Ensure consistent ordering of amounts, prices & multipliersPreviously, we have assumed that the `amounts` and `last_sale_prices`nlists have the same order as the `value_multipliers`. This is notncorrect, since to populate the `amounts` and `last_sale_prices` listsnwe iterate over a `dict` (self.positions). The order of this `dict`ncan change in arbitrary ways when it is updated, which occurs whennwe call `update_positions`. Our `value_multipliers` however are storednin an `OrderedDict`, meaning the order of existing key/value pairsnis not changed when they are updated.nnTo address this issue, we make sure that `self.positions` subclassesn`OrderedDict`.n

PERF: Remove memoization from minute bar position.Instead of using the `remember_last` memoization on all calls ton`_find_position_of_minute`, add an instance local cache which is onlynused by the `get_value` call. The `get_value` call is very hot, so anynextra overhead (e.g. creating the WeakArgs on every invocation) becomesncostly. The current usage `get_value` also has the property that it isncalled with monotonically increasing, but with a high repeat count onneach value. (A further improvement could making a `get_value` whichnsupports being used by many sids, for use by the update portfolionpositions.)nnThe caching is not done at the `_find_position_of_minute_level` becausen`unadjusted_window` always uses two positions on the tape (start and endnof range) which would cause the entries and removal into the cache whichnwould be invalidated both between the calls of start and end, and nextncall of the function.n

ENH: Add expiring cache.Add a cache interface which supports expirable entries with a changeablenbackend for the cache into which they are entered.nnThe default cache is a `dict` but could swapped forn`cachetools.LRUCache` or any other cache which supports `__get__`,n`__set__`, and `__del__`.nnSo that consumers can change the use of `CachedObjects` stored in ancache from:nn```nself._cache = {}nn...nntry:nobj = self._cache[key]ntry:nreturn obj.unwrap(dt)nexcept Expired:npassnexcept KeyError:npassnn...nnself._cache[key] = CachedObject(value, new_expiration)n```nnto:nn```nself._cache = ExpiringCache(LRUCache(maxsize=6))nn...nntry:nreturn self._cache.get(key, dt)nexcept KeyError:n# Get fresh valuen...nnself._cache.set(key, value, new_expiration)n```n

BUG: Add limit to memory growth on sliding windowsAdd a cap of 5 sliding windows (one per OHCLV column) to the historynloader's cache of sliding windos.nnThis prevents unbounded growth on algorithms that call history with anhighly varied list of equities.nnTo follow is splitting the cache up by column and by sid, so that thenloader does not re-prefetch sids which have already been read withnsufficient data; however this patch is enough to fix the issue where annalgo with high rotation can add up a megabyte per day of memory onnalgorithms which rotate on a 5% dollar volume pipeline. With this capnthose algorithms have more plateaus with regard to memory consumption.nnThis patch requires new dependency of `cachetools` library.n

BUG: Prevent out of order history arrays.Fix a bug where if history were called with assets `[1, 2]` and thennsubsequently, `[2, 1]`, the loader would return the cached array innorder for `[1, 2]`.nnInstead cache an AdjustedArray for each asset, then when a historynwindow is requested, check if each asset has a sufficient cache, and ifnnot then read values for the assets which are missing or need to benrefreshed.nnAn added benefit of this change is that if a subsequent call to historynhas a smaller number of assets than the previous, no new data needs tonbe read from disk. e.g. a call with assets `[1, 2, 3]` and then `[1, 2]`nwould use the cached values for `1` and `2` from the first call.nnConversely, if the second call has more assets, then only the data fornthe new assets needs to be retrieved. e.g. a history with `[1, 2]`, thenn`[1, 2, 3]` would only need (assuming `1` and `2` have not expired) tonretrieve data for `3`. Unfortunately, the benefit here is not greatnbecause `load_raw_arrays` is optimized for reading many assets, andnpulls the entire daily bar dataset into memory. This change makes tuningn`load_raw_arrays` so that faster reads (e.g. by slicing from the carraynfor each asset, instead of pulling all data into a numpy array), whennonly a few assets are requested, more beneficial than it would have beennpreviously.n

PERF: Improve read time for smaller num of assets.The BcolzDailyBarReader was optimized for the pipeline case of readingnall assets at once.nnNow that the reader is also used to support daily history the case ofnreading a data for a small number of assets is more common, particularlynin algorithms that use the history API which have a high rotation ofnassets (e.g. an algorithm which pipeline uses to set the activenuniverse)nnRemove the bottleneck in reading a small number of assets bynconditionally reading the slice for each asset from the carray, insteadnof reading the data for all equities and then indexing into that fullnarray. On a certain number of assets, it is still better to read all thendata at once. On the Quantopian dataset, which holds data for 20000nabout for the last 10 years of equity data (where not all equities tradenover the full range), stored in 118 blosc blp files per column, thentipping point where the 'read all' mode wins out between 3000-4000nassets.nnThat number was tested by trying to exercise a worst case scenario wherenthe equities were spread out evenly across the blp files, by steppingnalong a sorted list of assets that were alive over a query range whichnspanned 70 trading days.n```nsize = 3000nsids = [assets[i] for i in range(0, len(assets), len(assets) /nsize)][:size]n```nnAlso, add parameter to WithBcolzDailyBarReader fixture which allows thentest to specify what the threshold count for reading all data should be,nso that the test_us_equity_pricing can be forced into either mode tonmake sure that both branches in logic are covered by all test cases.nnOn local dev machine this patch improves the read time of `load_raw_array`nfor one asset from 100 ms to 96.5 u00c2u00b5s. (10^5 improvement.) With readingnonly asset per call a being an observed common case when populating thennon-cached values in USEquityHistoryLoader.n

ENH: Updates the cli, data bundles and extensions.Adds the data bundle concept which makes it easy for users to registernloading functions to build out minute and daily data along with annassets db and adjustments db. By default we have provided a `quandl`nbundle which pulls from the public domain WIKI dataset. Users maynregister new bundles by decorating an ingest function withn`zipline.data.bundles.register(<name>)`. This also provides an`yahoo_equities` function for creating an ingestion function that willnload a static set of assets from yahoo.nnThe cli is now structured as a couple of subcommands and has beennchanged to `python -m zipline`. The old behavior of `run_algo.py` hasnbeen moved to the `run` subcommand. This is almost entirely the samenexcept that it now takes the name of the data bundle to use, defaultingnto `quandl`.nnThe next subcommand is `ingest` which takes the name ofna data bundle to ingest. This will run the loading machinery and writenthe data to a specified location that `run` can find.nnThere is also a `clean` subcommand which deletes the data that wasnwritten with `ingest`.nnExtensions have also been added to zipline. This is an experimentalnfeature where users can provide an extra set of python files to run atnthe start of the process. These can be used to configure aspects ofnzipline. Right now the only thing that is supported in an extension filenis the registration of a new data bundle.n

ENH: Add support for strings in Pipeline.- Adds a new class, ``LabelArray``, which is a subclass of np.ndarray.n  LabelArray is conceptually similar to pandas.Categorical, in that itn  stores data with many duplicate values as indices into an array ofn  unique values.  For string data with many duplicates (e.g. time-seriesn  of tickers or or industry classifications), this provides multiplen  orders of magnitude of improvement when doing string operations,n  especially string comparison/matching operations.nn- Adds a new generic object specialization for `AdjustedArrayWindow`,n  and a corresponding ObjectOverwrite adjustment.nn- Adds a new ``postprocess`` method to ``zipline.pipeline.term.Term``.n  This method is called on the final result of any pipeline expressionn  after screen filtering has occurred. The default implementation ofn  ``postprocess`` is identity, but Classifier overrides it to coercen  string columns into pandas.Categoricals before presenting them to then  user.n

BUG: Apply latest adjustment for minute `1d`Fix behavior in minute mode history with frequency `1d`, where on thenday immediately following an adjustment action, the overnight adjustmentnwould not apply. (However the adjustment would be applied after a 1 daynlag.)nnThe root cause of the bug was that the history data for minute mode whennusing `1d` stitches together a sliding window of the daily data fornprevious  and the current minute. That daily data sliding window andncorresponding adjustments was being read as if the data was being viewednfrom on the last day of the window; however in this case the data isnbeing viewed from the day after the window has completed. The differencenin view points requires the adjustments to popped and applied by thenadjusted array one index earlier. The fix uses the `extra_slot` value asnsignifier on whether the data is being viewed on the following day andnthen accordingly adjusts the index of the mulitpy object.nnAlso, change the split and merger test data ratios to have different values,nto ensure that different adjustment values are applied; as opposed tondoubling up on just one of the values.n

BUG: Removes Hurricane Sandy closings from CME exchange calendarSince the CME calendar was based off of the NYSE calendar, closings fornHurricane Sandy were included, but shouldn't have been for CME.nnThis is the explanation we had included prior to the new exchangencalendars:nnhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurricane_sandynnWe *do not* add any non-trading days for Hurricane Sandy. Althoughntrading on CME Group exchanges was disrupted, trading still occurred atnsome point on each day. Importantly, the disruptions do not appear tonhave affected the expiration dates stipulated in the futures contractsnexpiring during this period.nnTrading of CME US equity index futures & NYMEX futures was disrupted duento the hurricane's impact on New York. CME US equity index futuresnmarkets were disrupted on October 29th 2012, but reopened at 5:00pm CT.nnThe US equity index markets were closed from 8:15am CT on October 30,nboth for the trading floor and CME Globex. The trading floor of thenNYMEX was closed on October 30, but all floor-trading products werenavailable electronically on CME Globex.nnSource:nhttp://investor.cmegroup.com/investor-relations/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=716923nnOctober 2012nSu Mo Tu We Th Fr San1  2  3  4  5  6n 7  8  9 10 11 12 13n14 15 16 17 18 19 20n21 22 23 24 25 26 27n28 29 30 31nnAlso see:n-- http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20121029/NEWS01/121029818/cme-cboe-other-markets-closed-for-hurricane-sandy-about-500-local-flights-scrappedn-- http://money.cnn.com/2012/10/29/investing/hurricane-sandy-stock-marketsn

MAINT: Refactor in prep for downsampled terms.- Split out extra_rows handling into an `ExecutionPlan` subclass.n  `ExecutionPlan` now requires the dates and calendar against which an  set of terms will be computed, and now defers to a term'sn  `compute_extra_rows` method when deciding how many extra rows aren  required to compute for that term. This will allow downsampled termsn  to request enough extra rows to guarantee that we can maintain consistentn  calculation dates.nn  As a consequence of the above, `TermGraph` now only deals with logicaln  dependencies, not with metadata surrounding extra row calculations.n  This means that TermGraph can be used to generate dependencyn  visualizations in interactive contexts where we don't yet have an  calendar or start/end dates.nn- Refactored test_{filter,factor,classifier} to use check_terms insteadn  of run_graph.  This makes it easier to make changes to TermGraph,n  since the testing interface is now to simply provide a dict of terms.nn- Refactored BasePipelineTestCase to use fixtures to create an assetn  finder.  This fixes a potential leak of the test's asset db, which wasn  not being explicitly cleaned up.nn- Refactored test_technical to use BasePipelineTestCase.nn- Added a new special term, `InputDates()`, which can be used to requestn  date labels for inputs.  Like `AssetExists`, `InputDates` is providedn  in the initial workspace by default.nn- Added a default (failing) `_compute` method to `AssetExists` whichn  provides a more useful error than AttributeError.n

ENH: Add support for downsampling.Adds a new ``downsample`` method to all computable terms.  Computablenterms (Filters, Factors, and Classifiers) can be downsampled to yearly,nquarterly, monthly, or weekly frequency.nnThe result of ``term.downsample`` is a new term of the samenfamily (Filter/Factor/Classifier) as ``term``.  The downsampled termncomputes by delegating to the original term; repeatedly calling itsn``compute`` method with length-1 date ranges.nnDownsampled terms take advantage of a new ``compute_extra_rows`` Termnmethod, which allows terms to dynamically request that additional extranrows of themselves be computed based on the dates for which they'renbeing computed.  This ensures, for example, that a monthly-downsamplednterm always computes at the start of a month, even when annaively-calculated pipeline window would end in the middle of the month.n

ENH: Add history for continuous futures.Enable unadjusted history for continuous futures.nnThe history array is filled by the values for the underlying contracts,nwhere the contract used changes based on rolls.nne.g., if a `1d` history window was over the rangen`2016-01-20` -> `2016-02-29` with contracts with a suffix of `F16` thatnrolls at the beginning of the session on `2016-01-26`, `G16` onn`2016-02-26`, and `H16` on `2016-03-26`. The `2016-01-20` ->n`2016-01-25` portion would use the values for `F16', the `2016-01-26` ->n`2016-02-25` portion would use `G16` and the `2016-02-26` ->n`2016-02-29` portion would use `H16`.nnUsing the same contracts as above, a `1m` history window over the rangen(using a timezone of US/Eastern) `2016-01-25 4:00PM` -> `2016-01-25n7:00PM` would fill the `4:00PM` -> `6:00PM` portion with data for `F16`nand the `6:01PM` -> `7:00PM` portion with data for `G16`, since thenbeginning of the `2016-01-26` session is `2016-01-25 6:01PM`.nnSupports `1d` and `1m`.nnAlso adds the `sid` field to `history` to assist in showing the activencontract at each dt in the window.n

This patch should also make it easier for history and pipelinento converge on a singular `load_adjustments` method.n

ENH: Add adjusted history for continuous futures.Add `.adj('mul')` and `.adj('add')` methods on ContinuousFuture, whichnwhen used with `history`, will calculate and apply adjustments so thatnthe values are adjusted to account for discounts and premiums duringnrolls.nnExample usage in an algo:nn```nfrom zipline.api import continuous_futurenndef initialize(context):ncontext.cl_add = continuous_future('CL', offset=0, roll='calendar').adj('add')ncontext.cl_mul = continuous_future('CL', offset=0, roll='calendar').adj('mul')ncontext.cl = continuous_future('CL', offset=0, roll='calendar')nschedule_function(print_history)nndef print_history(context, data):nframe = data.history([context.cl, context.cl_add, context.cl_mul],n ['price', 'sid'],n 20,n '1d')nprint 'unadjusted'nprint frame.loc[:, :, context.cl]nprint 'adjusted add'nprint frame.loc[:, :, context.cl_add]nprint 'adjusted mul'nprint frame.loc[:, :, context.cl_mul]n```n

BUG: Fix continuous future end dates.The end date of the last contract with a sufficient start date was beingnused for the continuous future overall end date; however the end date ofnthat contract (which is the last day for which there is data for thencontract) is not necessarily the greatest end date out of all contracts.nIt is possible for the furthest out contract to have some, but verynfew, trades before it is more actively traded. Which would give it anstart date within in the range of the simulation, but an end date isnearlier than the other contracts which are active during the simulation.nnThis bug would result in `nan`s when getting the current price becausenof the `end_date` check in `get_spot_value`. When the current simulationntime was greater than the `end_date` of the last contract the conditionnwhich guards against attempting to get data for an instrument past itsnend date would return a `nan`, even when the current underlying contractndid have data for that date.nnUse max end date of all contracts instead of the last one, to ensurenthat the continuous future last date is always great enough to allownaccess to all contracts with in the chain.nnAlso, use min start date to accurately mirror the end date behavior.n
Merge pull request #1587 from quantopian/fix-bug-for-continuous-future-max-dateBUG: Fix continuous future end dates.

BUG: Fix minute bar last traded after half day.When the following conditions occur,nn- a `nan` occurred after a half day (e.g. on the Monday afternThanksgiving, where the Friday would be a half day.)nn-data was written to the span between the early close and where the market closenwould have been if it were not an early close sessionnn- a `nan` also occured on the last minute of the early market session.nnthe exisitng implementation would incorrectly return a `nan` when requesting anforward filled price.nnThe steps that caused this error were.nn1. Request for `'price'` on the market open of the day after the early close.nn2. `nan` is found for that minutenn3. `get_last_traded_dt` is called, and finds a volume that occurs after thenearly close. e.g. `18:47` when the market close was `18:00`.nn4. The minute position for `18:47` is used, when callingn`find_positon_of_minute`, since that value is after the `market_close` thenminute is set to the position of `18:00`` due to the delta logic innn5. Since there is also no data in at `18:00`, a `nan` is returned, even thoughnthere were valid minutes earlier in the session. e.g. a non-zero volume atn`16:47` should have been used, but was not.nnFix by checking the current minute against the minute close when searching fornthe last traded minute. If the minute is greater than the market close for thencorresponding day, continue the search until the minute position is within thentrading session.nnThis could also be fixed by enforcing that only zeros can be written between annearly close and the minute where the close would have been, but this fix allowsnthe reader to work with existing data.n
Merge pull request #1594 from quantopian/fix-after-half-day-nanBUG: Fix minute bar last traded after half day.

TMP: Add temporary fix for transactions with nan fill prices.Protect a case where data is written with a non-zero volume, but a 0/nan for thenOHLC values. The slippage model was relying on a non-zero volume implying thatnthere was a valid trade price for the corresponding bar. When there was a mismatch,na transaction with a nan value was created, which would in turn propagate thennan into portfolio value, which would then cause errors when the portfolio valuenwas used to size orders during rebalancing.nnWhen data is fixed, can remove.n(Also may want to add behavior to minute bar writer to ensure that 0 volumesnalways have corresponding nan ohlc.)n
Merge pull request #1595 from quantopian/nan-check-transactinosTMP: Add temporary fix for transactions with nan fill prices.

PERF: Deterministically GC pipeline results.Any DataFrame that's had `.loc` or `.iloc `called on it participates inna cycle, which means they're not immediately garbage collected when theyngo out of scope.  This matters for pipeline results because they consumenmultiple megabytes per column, which means that a pipeline result withnmany columns can hold take up over 100MB.  By manually breakingnDataFrame cycles, we can ensure that we never hold multiple pipelinenresults in memory at once.n
PERF: Use searchsorted instead of get_loc.On pandas < 18, `get_loc` triggers allocation of a large hash table, sonwe don't want to call get_loc on minutely `DatetimeIndex`es.n

BUG: Fix bounds errors in roll finder.Fix common error condition which was triggered whenever the session at the endnof the prefetched history window was a session where the back contract wasnactive. When the back contract was the active contract, the next contract fornconsideration was the front contract at the end of the window, whichndefinitionally always has an autoclose after the end of the window.nInstead, just start seeking backwards from the end of the window.nnAlso prevent lookahead bias in volume rolls, which was caused by the using thenvolume for a session to determine whether that session had rolled. Informationnthat would not have been available at the beginning of the session.nnThis change makes the volume rolls overly conservative, and may be improved bynlooking at vectors of the preceding volume and making the roll off of momentum.n

(#1639)From pep-0008:rnrn```rnAlways use a def statement instead of an assignment statement that binds arnlambda expression directly to an identifier.rnrnYes:rnrndef f(x): return 2*xrnNo:rnrnf = lambda x: 2*xrnrnThe first form means that the name of the resulting function object isrnspecifically 'f' instead of the generic '<lambda>'. This is more useful forrntracebacks and string representations in general. The use of the assignmentrnstatement eliminates the sole benefit a lambda expression can offer over anrnexplicit def statement (i.e. that it can be embedded inside a larger expression)rn```

ENH: Align daily/minute bar lookbacks by default.When EQUITY_DAILY_BAR_SOURCE_FROM_MINUTE is set, usenEQUITY_MINUTE_BAR_LOOKBACK_DAYS as the default value fornEQUITY_DAILY_BAR_LOOKBACK_DAYS.nnWithout this, trying to run a minutely backtest in a test setting onlynEQUITY_MINUTE_BAR_LOOKBACK_DAYS and EQUITY_DAILY_BAR_SOURCE_FROM_MINUTEnfails because the benchmark creation process makes a daily history callnfor the entire period of the backtest, which then fails because thenequity daily bar calendar is shorter than the equity minute barncalendar.nnI can't imagine a circumstance in which you'd want the daily barncalendar to be shorter than the minute bar calendar when you're sourcingndaily bars from minutes, so this change makes that the default behaviornunless it's explicitly overridden.n

MAINT: Handle gaps in input to daily bars writer (#1778)Previously, a dataframe passed into BcolzDailyBarWriter.write that wasrnmissing an expected session between its first and last sessions would bernwritten incorrectly. Upon converting the dataframe to a ctable, thernvalues for all days following the gap would be shifted backwards, andrnnans would be shifted in at the end.rnrnThis commit handles the issue by asserting that the number of rows inrnthe input table matches the number of sessions in the calendar betweenrnthe table's first and last sessions.rnrnAlso fixes a test that was mistakenly using minutes_in_range where itrnshould have been using sessions_in_range (uncovered by this change).

PERF: Don't center dependents in vectorized_beta.The usual formula for covariance is::nn   mean((X - mean(X)) * (Y - mean(Y)))nnThis is equivalent, however, to just doing:nn   mean((X - mean(X)) * Y)nnProof:nnLet X_res = (X - mean(X)).nWe have:nnmean(X_res * (Y - mean(Y))) = mean(X_res * (Y - mean(Y)))n(1) = mean((X_res * Y) - (X_res * mean(Y)))n(2) = mean(X_res * Y) - mean(X_res * mean(Y))n(3) = mean(X_res * Y) - mean(X_res) * mean(Y)n(4) = mean(X_res * Y) - 0 * mean(Y)n(5) = mean(X_res * Y)nnThe tricky step in the above derivation is step (4). We know thatnmean(X_res) is zero because, for any X:nnmean(X - mean(X)) = mean(X) - mean(X) = 0.n

Improve price performance for 1000+ asset universes. (#2108)PERF: Optimize price for liquid assets.rnrnWhen using `price`, the call to `last_traded_dt` for every value retrievedrnbecame a noticeable bottleneck in algorithms which used over 1000 assets.rnrnInstead of calling `last_traded_dt` before every retrieval of a `close` for thern`price` field, assume that `close` will retrieve a non-empty value, and thenrnforward fill if it is empty.rnrnThis change optimizes for the case of a tradeable universe which is predominatelyrncomposed of liquid assets.

PERF: Variable-size minutely cache.Use a variable-size cache for minutely pricing data.nnIncrease the default cache size for close to 3000, since close pricesnare used in many places in the simulation as the best-known price ofnassets. This dramatically speeds up algorithms that read the prices ofnmany assets without ordering them.n

ENH: Initial support for international pipelines.This commit adds initial support for international markets in the Pipeline APInvia addition of the concept of domains.nnSignificant changes on this branch include:nn- Added `zipline.pipeline.domain` and the `Domain` interface.n  - Added several canonical domain definitions:n- GENERICn- US_EQUITIESn- CA_EQUITIESn- GB_EQUITIESnn- Added `zipline.country` as a place to define canonical country code names.nn- Made `PipelineLoader` an interface and added new `domain` parameter ton  signature of `load_adjusted_array`.nn- Added a new system for generic and specialized DataSet and BoundColumnn  objects.nn- Added a new system for inferring a domain from a pipeline that contains a mixn  of generic and non-generic terms.nn- Reworked the built-in pricing dataset. USEquityPricing dataset is now an  specialized version of a generic EquityPricing dataset, and most built-inn  factors are now implemented in terms of EquityPricing rather thann  USEquityPricing.nn- Removed `zipline.data.us_equity_pricing`.n  - Moved BcolzDailyBar{Reader,Writer} to `zipline.data.bcolz_daily_bars`.n  - Moved SQLiteAdjustment{Reader,Writer} to `zipline.data.adjustments`.nnNew dependencies added as part of this work:nn- iso3166 (for canonical country code definitions)n- python-interface (for strict interface definitions).nnSee https://github.com/quantopian/zipline/issues/2265 for a full description ofnthe design for domains.n

This warning is intended to prevent people fromndoing things like::nndf[df.col1 > 10]['col1'] = <value>nnwhich has no effect because the first [] creates a copy, which then getsnmutated, so the original frame remains unchanged.nnIn this case, however, we've bound the copy to a name that we're going toncontinue to use, so we don't care about the warning.n
