BUG: Fix _select_most_recent_symbols_chunk.Fixes a bug where _select_most_recent_symbols_chunk assumed that non-aggregatedncolumns in a GROUP BY expression would resolve to the first record in thengroup.nnPreviously we rendered a select like this:nn```nSELECT sid, symbol, company_symbol, share_class_symbol FROM (nSELECT sid, symbol, company_symbol, share_class_symbolnFROM equity_symbol_mappingsnWHERE sid IN (<list of sids>)nORDER_BY end_date ASCENDINGn)nGROUP BY sidn```nnIt appears that on older versions of SQLite, this reliably gave the last symbolnfor all symbol mappings associated with ``sid``, but on newer versions (or atnthe very least, in whatever configuration Travis is currently using), it's nonlonger the case.nnAs of this change we now render the following query instead:nn```nSELECT sid, symbol, company_symbol, share_class_symbol, max(end_date)nFROM equity_symbol_mappingsnWHERE sid IN (<list of sids>)nGROUP BY sidn```nnThis uses the fact that SQLite treats the max() and min() aggregation functionsnspecially for aggregation functions:nn> When the min() or max() aggregate functions are used in an aggregate query,n> all bare columns in the result set take values from the input row which alson> contains the minimum or maximum. Only the built-in min() and max() functionsn> work this way.n

BUG: fix selection of checkpoints at checkpoint boundaryWhen resolving data points to an output row index, we do not include recordsnwith a timestamp of _exactly_ the data query cutoff time:nnhttps://github.com/quantopian/zipline/blob/5cda2ad542cb1eab02a84a6685dfb3d2adabd44e/zipline/pipeline/loaders/blaze/_core.pyx#L566-L572nnhowever, when deciding which checkpoint to retrieve we would select anythingnless than *or equal to* the query start timestamp, after it had been adjusted tonthe data query cutoff time:nnhttps://github.com/quantopian/zipline/blob/5cda2ad542cb1eab02a84a6685dfb3d2adabd44e/zipline/pipeline/loaders/blaze/core.py#L1043-L1047nnIf we had a checkpoint at exactly the data query time, we would have selected itnmeaning all of the data would have a timestamp of exactly the data queryntime. We only select base rows between the checkpoint timestamp and the upperndt, so we would not have any base rows between the checkpoint and the firstnoutput index. When we go to slot these checkpoint rows into the output rows, wenwould shift them all forward one day leaving us with a leading missing rowninstead of the checkpoint data.nnThis change makes us select the most recent checkpoint strictly less than thenlower_dt which correctly gives us the checkpoint data on the first row of thenoutput when the query begins on a checkpoint boundary.n

BUG: Fix `week_start` when Monday precedes the New Year.The `week_start` date rule was incorrectly returning `False` forn`2018-12-31` on `NYSE` calendar.nnThe root cause of the bug was that the groupby used inn`TradingDayOfWeekRule.execution_period_values` was using the pairingnof `year` and `weekofyear`. This pairing grouped `2018-12-31` withnthe first week of January 2018 (`2018-01-02`, `2018-01-03`, ...),ninstead of with `2019-01-02`, `2019-01-03`, ...nnThis misgrouping occurred because the values of (year, weekofyear)nfor `2018-12-31` are (2018, 1); however the other dates that are in thensame week as `2018-12-31` have a value of (2019, 1).nnSince `2018-12-31` was misgrouped, the call to `nth(0)` would not selectnit as the first of the week; since it appeared to be the last day of thenfirst week of `2018`nnInstead, use the `isocalendar` method of the datetime object.nhttps://docs.python.org/2/library/datetime.html#datetime.date.isocalendarn`2018-12-31` is part of the ISO Week `2019-W01-1`, as are `2019-01-02`, etc.n(ISO Weeks location is determined by where the Thursday falls.)nnAlso, change the edge case tests so that a truth table of date andnexpected 'should trigger' result is defined.nnIn the previous version of the test, moving the start date beforenthe New Year was hitting edge cases within the test construction aroundnoffsets and calendar days.nMoving the first sim date would have been required to make sure thatna date like 2016-12-30 or 2018-12-31 was covered.nnThe change to use of the truth tables also takes the tests time down from 3.5nseconds to around 100ms on my dev machine.n

TEST: Clarify output for assert_dict_equal.Previously, for a large diff, I was getting output that looked like:nn```nAssertionError: extra key in result: set([u'timestamp'])nkeys do not matchnpath: _[u'CA'][u'table_1'][u'base'][u'indices'].viewkeys()nresult is missing key: set([u'indices'])nkeys do not matchnpath: _[u'CA'][u'table_2'][u'checkpoints'].viewkeys()nextra key in result: set([u'timestamp'])nkeys do not matchnpath: _[u'CA'][u'table_3'][u'base'][u'indices'].viewkeys()nresult is missing key: set([u'indices'])nkeys do not matchn```nnThis is hard to parse when there's a lot of it, because it's hard to see whichnlines should be grouped together.nnThe same output now looks like:nn```nAssertionError: keys do not matchnextra key in result: set([u'timestamp'])npath: _[u'CA'][u'table_1'][u'base'][u'indices'].viewkeys()n===nkeys do not matchnresult is missing key: set([u'indices'])npath: _[u'CA'][u'table_2'][u'checkpoints'].viewkeys()n===nkeys do not matchnextra key in result: set([u'timestamp'])npath: _[u'CA'][u'table_3'][u'base'][u'indices'].viewkeys()n```nnThis puts the most general statement (keys to not match) first, followed byndetails, and it makes it clearer which lines go together.n

ENH: Enable abstract DataSetFamily subclassesThis change enables us to define abstract subclasses of DataSetFamilynwhich implement some set of attributes, but don't represent tangiblenfamilies of DataSets, and thus don't have meaningful values forn`extra_dims`.nnPreviously, all subclasses of DataSetFamily had to define non-emptyn`extra_dims`. Subclasses were detected in DataSetFamilyMeta by checkingnif the base classes of the class under construction were specified asnanything other than the designated sentinel value: if so, `extra_dims`nwas transformed to an OrderedDict and checked for non-emptiness.nnWith this change, the metaclass instead checks for an `__abstract__`nattribute of the class under construction: if it is found and set to antruthy value, `extra_dims` (and `_SliceType`) is left unchecked andnunmodified. Regardless of its value, the `__abstract__` attribute isnremoved from the constructed class' body: each subclass which wishes tonremain abstract must specify this attribute again.n

ENH: Add PipelineHooks.Adds a new `PipelineHooks` interface for instrumenting Pipeline executions.nnHooks can be passed to on a per-invocation basis ton`SimplePipelineEngine.run_pipeline`/`SimplePipelineEngine.run_pipeline`. Theyncan also be passed to `SimplePipelineEngine` to be applied to all pipelinenexecutions.nnThere are several implementations of the `PipelineHooks` interface, but thenonly one useful to a user right now is `ProgressHooks`, which maintains a modelnof the progress of the execution and hands it off to a publisher class to bendisplayed to the user. The only interesting user-facing publisher isn`IPythonWidgetProgressPublisher`, which displays via an `ipywidgets` widget.n

BUG: Handle different counts of terms being computed between chunks.Fixes a bug where we miscomputed progress when the set of terms provided bynpopulate_initial_workspace changed between chunks.nnThe algorithm for accumulating progress is now as follows:nn1. For each chunk, compute the percentage of the pipeline execution that then   chunk will account for (we already did this to determine how to weight then   contribution of each term).nn2. Within each chunk, divide the total percentage to be completed by the numbern   of terms that will actually be loaded or computed. This required twon   upstream refactors:n   1. We now compute ``execution_order`` earlier and pass it ton  ``compute_chunk``.n   2. We now filter out pre-populated terms from ``execution_order``.nn3. For each term we load or compute, increment the total progress percentage byn   the value computed in (2).nnThe end result of this is that, at the end of each chunk, we should progress tonthe percentage that corresponds to the chunk end's location in the overallnpipeline execution. Within each chunk, we should progress by a uniform amountnwith each term. That uniform amount may vary from chunk to chunk however, if wencompute different numbers of terms in each chunk.n
